1. For get operation: If the key exists in the cache, move the entry to the most recently used (head) position in the cache and return the value associated with the key. Otherwise, return -1.
2. For put operation: If the key exists in the cache, update its value to the new one and move the entry to the most recently used (head) position in the cache. If the key does not exist and the cache has enough space, insert the new key-value pair to the cache with the key at the most recently used (head) position. If the key does not exist and the cache is full, evict the least recently used (tail) entry and insert the new key-value pair to the cache with the key at the most recently used (head) position.

In both implementations, we use a Map to keep track of the keys and values for constant time complexity get and put operations, and an additional List to maintain the order of the keys as they are accessed. This allows us to maintain the LRU Cache constraints and have an average time complexity of O(1) for both get and put operations.

